text: I have a little brother (not with down syndrome) but with a learning disability. Honestly I think one of the most captivating things about him & all others out their is their ability to truly tap into pure happiness & enjoyment. Sure there's moments of frustration, but you can't help but really smile & feel at ease when you learn to adapt to the same ease & chill attitude as them, but this is just context based on what I've learned growing alongside my little brother. He knows everyone in town, still takes pictures with firefighters and firetrucks, and heck he was popular in school they usually referred to me as hey you're *name*'s brother lol. Honestly I never minded, it was actually just funny to me since I saw he had a positive influence on others & I can proudly say it still remains true to this day & I could never ask for a better little brother than him üôèüèªüí™üèº

text: Nope. You almost had me though, right up until the moment that you had to introduce the audience to the love angle.   Would have been so much more pure, so much more transcendent if Tyler was able to help Zak without involvement from a beautiful character. The notion cheapens the friendship and distracts from the story, making it seem to the audience that such platitudes are necessary for us to be able to connect with the characters. And here, we can only venture so far involving an unorthodox friendship that the filmmakers essentially tell us that such altruism is fundamentally rewarded?   We can't just transcend for the sake of human-to-human sacredness? We have to be led to believe that there's some type of "atta boy" pat on the back in the form of a beautiful family member who will see Tyler's act of selflessness and thus reward him with her romantic involvement?   Get out of here with that crap.

text: This movie is literally everything... Everything. I don't even know how to articulate it... Shia LaBeouf might be kinda shattered, guarded and too visceral at times for some to fully understand or relate to, however, he's one of thee most beautifully exquisite, raw and talented artists of our time.  He transcends pain, sorrow and hope so effortlessly.  I'm in pure shock that this film didn't garner the recognition it truly deserved.  Shia should've won best performance. Zack Gottsagen, best supporting actor, hands down.  And the film itself should've won best film at the Oscars. Every single actor in the film, regardless of how small a part,  We're flawless.  The movie was a masterpiece. Definitely one of the best films I've ever seen. The trailer does NOT do it justice.

text: I think Shia LaBeouf wants so desperately to be real... he's getting there, I'm proud to say.  Real doesn't just recognize real - real recognizes everything.  He doesn't want to be another actor.  He wants to seize the fucking day while it may be had.  He takes his characters and cannibalizes them - ingesting their souls and emblazoning them with technicolor.  His angst about his father is key to his brilliance... unfortunately.  It's a double-edged sword.  I love Shia because he stands out - he is boiling with such immense potential.  For awhile I thought he might break - perhaps he did.  But - as I had hoped - he is an overcomer.  ...and the things he had to overcome are not trivial.  When I observe Shia, I observe an everyman - perhaps an Ubermensch.    As someone who had to deal with abandonment issues, I "feel" Shia... I would like to hang out with him and talk about it, as we freaks have precious few who can kind of understand.  I know - that people with childhood trauma do not really have that many people to talk to - not really... so we internalize.  But in doing that, we skirt the fringes of sanity... and we few who actually make it... who actually learn how to view other people as ... well... real people, usually end up being the most interesting people on Earth.  That void is continually filled with things we are interested in - and in the end... there's nothing we're not interested in.  Shia is going to do what he wants.  He will find an unexpected success - and it will just get better and better as he learns to crawl out of the crucible of suffering that he has been accustomed to.  I do not follow actors, or anyone, really - but Shia seems to be a kindred spirit.. His energy resonates with my own - and that, to me, is compelling.
